{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492617","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492617"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:37:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:37:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1112"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1112","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1112"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.01,0.32,0.57,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1112"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"28387"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1112","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1112"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1112"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"14665"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"329"},{"type":"tags","id":"1156"},{"type":"tags","id":"2091"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5446"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7012"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44934"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"28387","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/28387"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 29-year-old man presents to his general practitioner with a one week history of an intermittent painful swelling under his jaw. The pain and swelling is worse before and during eating; while the pain is bothersome, it does not stop him from eating or drinking. He is otherwise well and, while he eats a healthy and varied diet, he admits that he does not drink as much water as he would like, and he has a 10 pack-year smoking history. On examination, he is afebrile and looks well. The following view is obtained on an intra-oral examination (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ultrasound of the jaw","Amitriptyline 25mg nocte","Encourage increased hydration and sucking on lemon drops","Refer to ENT specialist for stone removal","Dicloxacillin 500mg QID"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Ereferral to an ENT specialist for stone removal\u003C/strong\u003E. This patient has a submandibular duct stone (sialolithiasis) visible on inspection of the oral cavity. The stone is large and unlikely to pass spontaneously with conservative management, so referral to a surgeon is warranted.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf the stone was smaller, conservative measures such as \u003Cstrong\u003Eencouraging increased hydration and sucking on lemon drops\u003C/strong\u003E would likely suffice. Most cases of sialolithiasis respond to conservative management, including staying well-hydrated and using agents that promote salivary flow such as hard candies. In addition, massaging the salivary glands to \u0022milk\u0022 the duct may help.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUltrasound of the jaw\u003C/strong\u003E, while a non-invasive imaging method that does not require radiation, is not required in this case as the stone is clearly visible. Imaging for sialolithiasis is only required if the diagnosis is unclear or if a tumour is suspected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmitriptyline \u003C/strong\u003Eis a poor choice for several reasons. Firstly, amitriptyline is used more for chronic pain, rather than acute pain. Secondly, amitriptyline can reduce salivary flow through its anticholinergic effects, which will make it harder for the body to flush out the stone. In fact, another aspect of conservative management is discontinuation of anticholinergic medications (if possible).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDicloxacillin 500mg QID\u003C/strong\u003E can be used if a secondary infection is suspected. However, the patient is well and afebrile, and he is not in significant pain, making infection unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Conservative management is the mainstay of treatment for sialolithiasis"],"references":["Burke CJ, Thomas RH, Howlett D. Imaging the major salivary glands. Br J Oral Maxillofac Surg. 2011 Jun;49(4):261-9. doi: 10.1016/j.bjoms.2010.03.002.","Williams MF. Sialolithiasis. Otolaryngol Clin North Am. 1999 Oct;32(5):819-34. doi: 10.1016/s0030-6665(05)70175-4."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"14665"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1112"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17384"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17384","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17384"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/af9e1598-172d-47ce-af7b-3452da4bb8a6.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/af9e1598-172d-47ce-af7b-3452da4bb8a6.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":570}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"14665","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/14665"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2022-09-19T17:09:34+09:30","updatedAt":"2022-09-19T17:09:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1112"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"28387"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/35"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc43","name":"Otorhinolaryngology","synonyms":["ENT","HEENT"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"upda